Here is an incredible story about Ozy, a digital media startup. Ozy was loo=
king to raise a $40 million investment from Goldman Sachs Group Inc.=E2=80=
=99s asset management arm, on the strength of the traffic to its=C2=A0websi=
te, newsletters and YouTube videos. As part of its due diligence, Goldman w=
anted to do a call with YouTube. Carlos Watson, the =E2=80=9Ccharismatic ch=
ief executive=E2=80=9D of Ozy, gave Goldman a Gmail address for YouTube exe=
cutive Alex Piper, and Ozy set up a call between Piper and Goldman in early=
 February.On the call, Piper said nice things about Ozy, but =E2=80=9Cthe m=
an=E2=80=99s voice began to sound strange to the Goldman Sachs team, as tho=
ugh it might have been digitally altered.=E2=80=9D So Goldman =E2=80=9Creac=
hed out to Mr. Piper, not through the Gmail address that Mr. Watson had pro=
vided before the meeting, but through Mr. Piper=E2=80=99s assistant at YouT=
ube.=E2=80=9D And it turned out he had not been on the call: Samir Rao, Ozy=
=E2=80=99s co-founder and chief operating officer, had allegedly=C2=A0been =
impersonating him in order to trick Goldman into investing in Ozy.[1]Ordina=
rily if I were telling you this story I=E2=80=99d be quoting from a federal=
 criminal complaint, or at least a Securities and Exchange Commission enfor=
cement action, but nope everything is fine! I=E2=80=99m quoting from a New =
York Times column by Ben Smith, nobody has been charged with anything, and =
Watson and Rao remain at Ozy and keep raising money. (Not from Goldman, whi=
ch passed on the deal, but =E2=80=9Cin April, two months after Goldman Sach=
s walked away, the company raised another round of financing.=E2=80=9D) Smi=
th writes:In his apology to Goldman Sachs and in an email to me on Friday, =
Mr. Watson attributed the incident to a mental health crisis and shared wha=
t he said were details of Mr. Rao=E2=80=99s diagnosis.=E2=80=9CSamir is a v=
alued colleague and a close friend,=E2=80=9D Mr. Watson said. =E2=80=9CI=E2=
=80=99m proud that we stood by him while he struggled, and we=E2=80=99re al=
l glad to see him now thriving again.=E2=80=9DHe added that Mr. Rao took ti=
me off from work after the call and is now back at Ozy. Mr. Rao did not rep=
ly to requests for comment.Marc Lasry, a hedge fund manager, a co-owner of =
the Milwaukee Bucks basketball team and chairman of the Ozy board, said in =
a statement: =E2=80=9CThe board was made aware of the incident, and we full=
y support the way it was handled. The incident was an unfortunate one-time =
event, and Carlos and his team showed the kind of compassion we would all w=
ant if any of us faced a difficult situation in our own lives.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=A6Goldman Sachs took no further action after the call with the Ozy exec=
utive who had apparently impersonated the YouTube executive. But the securi=
ty team at Google, which owns YouTube, determined a crime might have been c=
ommitted.Google has alerted the Federal Bureau of Investigation, two people=
 with knowledge of the matter said. Goldman Sachs then received an inquiry =
from federal law enforcement officials, one person with knowledge of that i=
nquiry said.The guy=C2=A0impersonated a YouTube executive to trick someone=
=C2=A0into investing?=C2=A0You=E2=80=99re just not going to get an easier s=
ecurities fraud case than that, and neither =E2=80=9Cit didn=E2=80=99t work=
=E2=80=9D nor =E2=80=9Che was having a tough time=E2=80=9D nor =E2=80=9Cit =
only happened once=E2=80=9D are generally defenses to fraud charges! Ozy=E2=
=80=99s board =E2=80=9Cdid not formally investigate=E2=80=9D! The CEO of th=
e company gave a potential investor a fake email address for a big customer=
, and then the COO digitally altered his voice to impersonate that customer=
 on a call with the investor, and the board decided not to investigate beca=
use ... they were satisfied that this was just a one-time thing, a little o=
opsie,=C2=A0everything else that the company does is completely aboveboard,=
 and anyway no harm no foul?Here=E2=80=99s  the thing about being a private=
 company. You can sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0say stuff. If you are a public com=
pany and you say =E2=80=9Cwe have the highest traffic of any media site in =
the world,=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s not true, someone will sue you for sec=
urities fraud. Everything you say in public,=C2=A0you say to investors, and=
 if it=E2=80=99s wrong you get in trouble. If you are a private company and=
 you say =E2=80=9Cwe have the highest traffic of any media site in the worl=
d,=E2=80=9D there can be various footnotes and caveats that you think but d=
on=E2=80=99t say, you can cross=C2=A0your fingers behind your back, it=E2=
=80=99s fine. You don=E2=80=99t have to follow generally accepted accountin=
g principles or use words in their ordinary meanings in your public stateme=
nts.[2] The public can=E2=80=99t buy your stock so it doesn=E2=80=99t matte=
r. You sell stock only occasionally, in negotiated transactions with sophis=
ticated investors; you sign agreements with those investors in which they e=
ssentially disclaim any reliance on anything that you=E2=80=99ve said outsi=
de of the deal documents.=C2=A0But! When those sophisticated investors do t=
heir due diligence, they will ask you specific questions. You will say in p=
ublic =E2=80=9Cwe have the highest traffic of any media site in the world,=
=E2=80=9D and the investors will send you a list of questions like =E2=80=
=9Chow many unique visitors did you have in each of the last 12=C2=A0months=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdescribe all commercial arrangements in which you pa=
y for traffic=E2=80=9D and other stuff designed to tease out exactly how bi=
g and good your traffic is. They will do this because they are sophisticate=
d investors; they understand that your public statements are for different =
audiences, and that in any case you are a  visionary private-company founde=
r and when you say stuff it sometimes reflects your confidence in your comp=
any=E2=80=99s bright future rather than present-day reality. So they will j=
ust quietly, behind the scenes, ask you boring factual questions to see how=
 close your claims are to reality. And you will respond with the boring fac=
tual answers. And if those answers don=E2=80=99t quite correspond to your b=
old claims then, you know, that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s how startups=
 work; they won=E2=80=99t necessarily pass on the investment just because t=
he boring financial reality of your business doesn=E2=80=99t yet match your=
 vision.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s just that=C2=A0if you lie to them in due diligen=
ce that ruins the whole deal. If they ask for a customer call during due di=
ligence, and you impersonate the customer to give them the answers you want=
 them to hear, come on, come on, come on, come on.Here=E2=80=99s another th=
ing about being a private company. What if this had worked? What if Goldman=
 hadn=E2=80=99t noticed anything unusual and had coughed up the $40 million=
? Wouldn=E2=80=99t Goldman have been embarrassed when this story came out? =
Well, no, because this story never would have come out! Even if someone had=
 told Goldman after the fact =E2=80=9Chey that call with YouTube was fake,=
=E2=80=9D what would they have done about it? They could call Ozy and deman=
d their money back but presumably Ozy=C2=A0spent it. They could sue, but ho=
w much would they be able to recover? Once you=E2=80=99ve been=C2=A0tricked=
 into investing in a high-flying startup, the only rational move is to hope=
 that they succeed, clean up their act and go public at a higher valuation.=
 You=E2=80=99d never go around saying =E2=80=9Cwe were tricked=E2=80=9D; th=
at just destroys value.Similarly,=C2=A0if you are an=C2=A0investor and boar=
d member of a hot startup, and you find out that the co-founder impersonate=
d a customer to try to trick someone into investing, what are your incentiv=
es? If you make a big deal about it and throw around words like =E2=80=9Cfr=
aud,=E2=80=9D it will be hard for the startup ever to raise money again, wh=
ich might make your own investment worthless. If you say, meh, unfortunate =
one-time event, no harm no foul, then maybe the company=E2=80=99s vision wi=
ll end up working out and you=E2=80=99ll be able to sell=C2=A0at a profit. =
If you invest in a startup you are buying an option; your goal, as a board =
member, is not to extinguish the option value too soon. Just, you know, let=
 it ride, see where this goes.I am appalled, sure,=C2=A0but honestly=C2=A0I=
 also admire it a bit. I feel like there is some threshold of absolute sham=
elessness that most companies cannot even aspire to, but if you reach it=C2=
=A0then either you blow up in short order or you take over the world. I=E2=
=80=99ll probably=C2=A0be working for Ozy in a year.
