</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way corporate law generally works =
in the U.S. is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40p=
x; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Corporate law is a=
 matter of=C2=A0<em>state=C2=A0</em>law. Securities law is federal =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if companies lie about their securities to raise money they get in=
 federal trouble=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0<em>corporate=C2=A0</em>law, =
and in particular the fiduciary duties of directors to shareholders, is sta=
te law. Delaware law, mostly, because big U.S.=C2=A0public companies are mo=
stly incorporated in Delaware, and Delaware has specialized judges who are =
good at business law.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Corporate la=
w is generally deferential to directors. If the directors make a decision o=
n behalf of the company, and a shareholder disagrees, and the shareholder c=
omes to a Delaware court saying =E2=80=9Cthis company introduced a big new =
smartphone but I think that a smaller phone would fit in my hands=C2=A0bett=
er,=E2=80=9D the court will not be interested. The =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgme=
nt rule=E2=80=9D generally requires courts to defer to directors=E2=80=99 b=
usiness decisions. There are exceptions where a court will scrutinize direc=
tors=E2=80=99 decisions more closely, but generally that requires the share=
holder to prove some conflict of interest, some personal interest of the di=
rector that makes it impossible for her to be loyal to shareholders.</li></=
ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if we reversed that? What if we made c=
orporate law federal, and required courts to reverse directors=E2=80=99 bus=
iness decisions=C2=A0unless the=C2=A0<em>directors=C2=A0</em>could <em>prov=
e=C2=A0</em>that they were the correct decisions? You don=E2=80=99t like th=
e size of the new iPhone, you sue Apple Inc. in=C2=A0federal court anywhere=
 in the U.S., and then the burden is on Apple to prove to a jury that the n=
ew iPhone is the right size. If the jury disagrees then the directors are p=
ersonally liable for damages.=C2=A0Would this be a good system?</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No, come on, that is the dumbest=C2=A0paragraph I have=
 typed in 10 years of typing paragraphs about business, but here we are, he=
re we are, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2516099=
